WEBVTT

00:05.506 --> 00:07.174
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

00:07.174 --> 00:09.760
<i>- Tonight, we continue</i>
<i>our first ever</i>

00:09.760 --> 00:12.721
"Forged in Fire"
invitational tournament.

00:12.721 --> 00:15.015
<i>Over five weeks,</i>
<i>four classes</i>

00:15.015 --> 00:18.018
<i>of metalsmithing</i>
<i>professionals, farriers,</i>

00:18.018 --> 00:21.021
<i>armorers, blacksmiths,</i>
<i>and modern metalworkers</i>

00:21.021 --> 00:24.274
<i>will put their blademaking</i>
<i>skills to the test.</i>

00:24.274 --> 00:27.319
It's the first time where
all four of our bladesmiths

00:27.319 --> 00:30.280
<i>come from a similar</i>
<i>metalworking class.</i>

00:30.280 --> 00:32.824
<i>The winner from each class</i>
<i>will go head to head</i>

00:32.824 --> 00:34.993
<i>for a chance at the title</i>
<i>of tournament champion,</i>

00:34.993 --> 00:37.329
<i>and the biggest purse ever.</i>

00:37.329 --> 00:38.747
$50,000.

00:38.747 --> 00:40.582
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:40.582 --> 00:44.294
<i>Right now, round two</i>
<i>belongs to the armorers.</i>

00:44.294 --> 00:47.339
<i>Four armorers bring their</i>
<i>unique skills to the forge.</i>

00:47.339 --> 00:49.174
- I'm feeling good,
I'm feeling good, yeah.

00:49.174 --> 00:50.801
- I'm so impressed with the way

00:50.801 --> 00:53.345
that these guys
hand move metal.

00:53.345 --> 00:56.098
<i>To compete for the honor</i>
<i>of representing their class</i>

00:56.098 --> 00:59.643
<i>in the "Forged in Fire"</i>
<i>Tournament of Champions.</i>

00:59.643 --> 01:01.436
<i>[metal clangs]</i>

01:01.436 --> 01:04.398
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

01:04.398 --> 01:08.694
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:08.694 --> 01:10.320
<i>- My name is</i>
<i>Nicholas Cochilla.</i>

01:10.320 --> 01:12.698
Being an armorer, there's
a whole lot of knowledge

01:12.698 --> 01:14.741
that has to go into
being able to make

01:14.741 --> 01:16.493
<i>a serviceable suit of armor.</i>

01:16.493 --> 01:18.745
There's quite a bit of
math, geometry,

01:18.745 --> 01:20.455
<i>and artistry</i>
<i>that goes into it.</i>

01:20.455 --> 01:23.250
Armor is hard.
Knives are easy.

01:23.250 --> 01:25.627
<i>- I am Ryan Weaver.</i>

01:25.627 --> 01:30.757
I compete in full force,
full contact steel combat.

01:30.757 --> 01:34.428
<i>I like to point out that I'm</i>
<i>a better lover than a fighter,</i>

01:34.428 --> 01:38.640
but I'm still a pretty
damn good fighter.

01:38.640 --> 01:41.435
- My name is Howard Noble.
I am a full-time armorer.

01:41.435 --> 01:43.520
I work in the shop
six days a week.

01:43.520 --> 01:45.480
<i>I supply a lot of</i>
<i>medieval groups,</i>

01:45.480 --> 01:47.274
<i>reenactors, collectors.</i>

01:47.274 --> 01:48.692
<i>By doing this, I'm hoping that</i>

01:48.692 --> 01:50.444
people will take notice
of armorers.

01:50.444 --> 01:52.487
It's not an easy job.

01:52.487 --> 01:56.033
- My name is Jacob Danker.
Forging is kind of my thing.

01:56.033 --> 01:59.244
<i>It takes me back, literally,</i>
<i>to like, the dawn of time</i>

01:59.244 --> 02:02.080
<i>where man was just trying</i>
<i>to figure out tools.</i>

02:02.080 --> 02:04.249
I really think there's
something like, beautiful

02:04.249 --> 02:07.586
in taking a lump of steel
and turning it into armor,

02:07.586 --> 02:11.340
a knife, and it's just
a very primal feeling.

02:11.340 --> 02:12.841
<i>[tense music]</i>

02:12.841 --> 02:15.385
- Armorers, welcome to
our first ever

02:15.385 --> 02:18.180
"Forged in Fire"
invitational tournament.

02:18.180 --> 02:20.682
Today, you armorers
will have to survive

02:20.682 --> 02:23.602
three rounds of competition
designed to test

02:23.602 --> 02:26.313
every aspect of your
bladesmithing capabilities,

02:26.313 --> 02:28.190
all in front of our panel
of expert judges.

02:28.190 --> 02:30.233
Let's meet them now.

02:30.233 --> 02:33.111
Up first, knife maker
Ben Abbott.

02:33.111 --> 02:36.156
Next, sword maker David Baker.

02:36.156 --> 02:39.826
And last, life-taker,
Doug Marcaida.

02:39.826 --> 02:42.412
Here at The Forge,
we pride ourselves

02:42.412 --> 02:44.122
on creating each round

02:44.122 --> 02:46.708
to separate the good
from the exceptional.

02:46.708 --> 02:48.043
Today, we're going to find

02:48.043 --> 02:50.837
the chinks in your armor
using this.

02:50.837 --> 02:53.757
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

02:53.757 --> 02:58.804
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:58.804 --> 03:00.931
This should all be
really familiar to you guys.

03:00.931 --> 03:02.974
<i>While protective gear</i>
<i>has been in use</i>

03:02.974 --> 03:05.560
<i>beyond written history,</i>
<i>steel-plated armor</i>

03:05.560 --> 03:08.689
<i>emerged in the 13th century,</i>
<i>and became more defensive,</i>

03:08.689 --> 03:12.025
<i>intricate, and exquisite</i>
<i>in the centuries following.</i>

03:12.025 --> 03:14.444
<i>While the advent of firearms</i>
<i>rendered armor suiting</i>

03:14.444 --> 03:17.406
<i>obsolete, the craft of</i>
<i>those armorers lived on.</i>

03:17.406 --> 03:20.534
<i>In fact, NASA examined a set</i>
<i>of Henry VIII's armor</i>

03:20.534 --> 03:23.328
<i>when designing</i>
<i>the first spacesuits.</i>

03:23.328 --> 03:27.124
Your challenge is to salvage
at least three pieces of metal

03:27.124 --> 03:31.795
from this armor and combine it
with the 1095 and 15N20

03:31.795 --> 03:35.173
<i>from which you will forge</i>
<i>a layered Damascus blade.</i>

03:35.173 --> 03:38.427
<i>- For an armorer,</i>
<i>the mention of Damascus</i>

03:38.427 --> 03:41.763
is like asking if we like
the hamburgers

03:41.763 --> 03:43.932
in a country
we've never been to.

03:43.932 --> 03:48.437
<i>It's just definitely outside</i>
<i>of my comfort zone.</i>

03:48.437 --> 03:50.272
- Keep in mind that
in the second round,

03:50.272 --> 03:52.149
you'll be attaching handles
to those blades,

03:52.149 --> 03:54.443
and then, they'll be tested
for strength and durability

03:54.443 --> 03:56.153
<i>in a helmet chop,</i>

03:56.153 --> 04:00.490
and for edge retention
in a quilted armor slice.

04:00.490 --> 04:02.159
You'll have ten minutes
to work on your designs.

04:02.159 --> 04:03.994
You will have three hours
to forge your blades.

04:03.994 --> 04:05.996
Good luck.

04:05.996 --> 04:08.165
Your ten-minute design window
starts now.

04:08.165 --> 04:10.625
<i>[rock music]</i>

04:10.625 --> 04:12.961
The task at hand
is to create a billet

04:12.961 --> 04:16.465
from which to forge a layered
Damascus pattern blade.

04:16.465 --> 04:18.633
How difficult
is this challenge?

04:18.633 --> 04:20.177
- It's harder when you're
wearing a helmet, though.

04:20.177 --> 04:22.345
[laughter]

04:22.345 --> 04:24.139
<i>- I was a little concerned</i>
<i>maybe some of</i>

04:24.139 --> 04:26.308
the other armorers
would be intimidated by me,

04:26.308 --> 04:27.976
and try to take me out
from behind.

04:27.976 --> 04:29.686
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:29.686 --> 04:33.565
I'm designing a blade
based off of a kinjal.

04:33.565 --> 04:36.067
<i>I'm wanting to add</i>
<i>a little bit of mass</i>

04:36.067 --> 04:38.153
<i>out toward</i>
<i>the end of the blade</i>

04:38.153 --> 04:41.323
<i>to help with the helmet chop.</i>

04:41.323 --> 04:45.160
- The knife that I'm designing
is definitely a chopper.

04:45.160 --> 04:47.454
<i>I want to make sure that</i>
<i>my blade survives the test,</i>

04:47.454 --> 04:49.956
<i>so it's got a heavy spine</i>
<i>and a straight edge.</i>

04:49.956 --> 04:52.501
<i>The biggest concern I have</i>
<i>is the time factor.</i>

04:52.501 --> 04:54.169
I'm used to working on projects

04:54.169 --> 04:56.588
that take sometimes days
to produce.

04:56.588 --> 04:58.715
<i>Now, I've got to do it in just</i>
<i>a three-hour time window.</i>

04:58.715 --> 05:00.467
<i>Very difficult.</i>

05:00.467 --> 05:02.052
<i>[rock music]</i>

05:02.052 --> 05:04.095
<i>- I can make a knife</i>
<i>pretty fast.</i>

05:04.095 --> 05:07.516
You want me to make a Damascus
knife in the same time?

05:07.516 --> 05:09.726
<i>It's quite a challenge.</i>

05:09.726 --> 05:12.854
I'm designing
a competition chopper.

05:12.854 --> 05:15.315
<i>Make it a little thicker than</i>
<i>I normally would make a knife,</i>

05:15.315 --> 05:18.276
<i>so it'll withstand the impact</i>
<i>to a helmet.</i>

05:18.276 --> 05:21.154
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:21.154 --> 05:22.364
- I don't think
the other competitors

05:22.364 --> 05:24.324
take me very seriously.

05:24.324 --> 05:25.951
<i>They seem kind of like,</i>
<i>old geezers.</i>

05:25.951 --> 05:28.161
<i>So I'm the young guy.</i>

05:28.161 --> 05:30.080
I could come out--
underdog story.

05:30.080 --> 05:31.998
I'm all about the underdog.

05:31.998 --> 05:33.291
<i>The challenges include</i>
<i>a helmet chop,</i>

05:33.291 --> 05:35.418
<i>and a quilted armor slice.</i>

05:35.418 --> 05:39.631
<i>And I feel like a Bowie is</i>
<i>perfect for those challenges.</i>

05:39.631 --> 05:42.759
<i>I'm just going to implement</i>
<i>a sheepsfoot head on it.</i>

05:42.759 --> 05:44.594
- Your ten-minute
design window has closed.

05:44.594 --> 05:46.972
Your three-hour forge
time starts...

05:46.972 --> 05:48.515
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

05:48.515 --> 05:49.599
Now.

05:49.599 --> 05:51.351
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:51.351 --> 05:53.478
- I really want to
see these guys go above

05:53.478 --> 05:55.313
the three layers
that they have to take.

05:55.313 --> 05:57.190
<i>- So I see this</i>
<i>big pile of armor,</i>

05:57.190 --> 05:59.109
<i>and I'm thinking to myself,</i>
<i>"Just don't be painted;</i>

05:59.109 --> 06:00.569
don't be covered in oil."

06:00.569 --> 06:02.487
I get over there,
and it's covered in oil,

06:02.487 --> 06:04.531
and it's painted on the back.

06:04.531 --> 06:06.074
- The most important thing

06:06.074 --> 06:07.993
with doing any kind of
stacked billet

06:07.993 --> 06:10.120
is, make sure your metal
is clean.

06:10.120 --> 06:12.873
The paint and oil
can cause delamination.

06:12.873 --> 06:14.749
<i>- It's all stuff</i>
<i>you have to grind off.</i>

06:14.749 --> 06:16.918
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:16.918 --> 06:20.130
<i>- To make a Damascus,</i>
<i>you need flat pieces of metal.</i>

06:20.130 --> 06:22.716
- That particular piece
of armor is a back plate,

06:22.716 --> 06:24.759
and that's a really good
piece of steel as well,

06:24.759 --> 06:27.262
because it gives you
the flat pieces you need.

06:27.262 --> 06:29.514
- I've never made a knife out
of armor before.

06:29.514 --> 06:31.600
First time.
So it's a new experience.

06:31.600 --> 06:33.435
The learning curve
just got accelerated.

06:33.435 --> 06:35.395
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:35.395 --> 06:37.314
<i>- An armorer is different</i>
<i>than a blacksmith</i>

06:37.314 --> 06:40.317
because they are the expert
at mapping metal

06:40.317 --> 06:42.652
around the human body,
and actually looking

06:42.652 --> 06:45.071
for the articulation
where it needs to be.

06:45.071 --> 06:46.656
It's a very precise deal.

06:46.656 --> 06:48.283
[chuckles]

06:48.283 --> 06:50.327
<i>Honestly,</i>
<i>I'm most worried about</i>

06:50.327 --> 06:53.079
not getting
a forge weld sticking.

06:53.079 --> 06:56.416
But if I can get that weld
to stick, boom, we're solid.

06:56.416 --> 06:59.377
<i>[rock music]</i>

06:59.377 --> 07:01.254
<i>I just got</i>
<i>the first forge weld</i>

07:01.254 --> 07:03.632
<i>all tied in together.</i>

07:03.632 --> 07:05.258
And I'm just
on top of a mountain,

07:05.258 --> 07:08.136
just thinking
it's all gravy from here.

07:08.136 --> 07:10.680
I'm feeling good,
I'm feeling good, yeah, yeah.

07:10.680 --> 07:12.223
[laughs]

07:12.223 --> 07:13.266
- What's the skirt
at the bottom

07:13.266 --> 07:14.726
of the breastplate called?

07:14.726 --> 07:16.353
- When it's big,
it's a culet.

07:16.353 --> 07:17.729
- On your hands,
they're gauntlets, right?

07:17.729 --> 07:18.855
- Gauntlets, yeah.
- Gauntlets--

07:18.855 --> 07:20.774
- Vambrace.
- Vambrace.

07:20.774 --> 07:23.026
- Elbow, rerebrace, spaulder.
- Rerebrace and spaulder.

07:23.026 --> 07:24.319
- You guys are nerds, man.
- Cuisses.

07:24.319 --> 07:26.321
- [laughs]

07:26.321 --> 07:28.865
<i>- I decided to use</i>
<i>the pauldron and spaulders,</i>

07:28.865 --> 07:31.409
which are shoulder
and upper arm covering.

07:31.409 --> 07:34.371
<i>They're only rolled in</i>
<i>essentially one plane,</i>

07:34.371 --> 07:37.374
<i>so they should be easier</i>
<i>to flatten out.</i>

07:37.374 --> 07:39.584
- There's Ryan,
having to flatten

07:39.584 --> 07:41.586
all those pieces
that were curved.

07:41.586 --> 07:48.134
- Armorers tend to be really
focused on the small details.

07:48.134 --> 07:51.346
<i>I feel like I'm in my</i>
<i>comfort zone, as far as speed.</i>

07:51.346 --> 07:54.057
Slow and steady wins the race.

07:54.057 --> 07:55.517
<i>- So I'm putting</i>
<i>my stack together,</i>

07:55.517 --> 07:57.310
<i>I'm trying to get it clean,</i>

07:57.310 --> 08:00.063
I'm still sanding,
trying to get my pieces clean,

08:00.063 --> 08:01.981
<i>and I hear</i>
<i>the power hammer going.</i>

08:01.981 --> 08:04.484
<i>There's guys already</i>
<i>shaping their billets.</i>

08:04.484 --> 08:07.904
This makes me worried.
I'm already the last in line.

08:07.904 --> 08:09.864
- One hour has elapsed!

08:09.864 --> 08:12.617
You have two hours remaining
to finish your work!

08:12.617 --> 08:15.453
In this armorers'
first round of competition,

08:15.453 --> 08:17.789
a lot more racket
from Big Blue

08:17.789 --> 08:20.792
than we had in the farriers'
first round of competition.

08:20.792 --> 08:23.211
- Yeah, the farriers tended
to do more with the hammer,

08:23.211 --> 08:25.004
and less with the power tool.

08:25.004 --> 08:27.048
- You know, if you walk into
an armorer's workshop,

08:27.048 --> 08:29.801
there are tools everywhere.

08:29.801 --> 08:32.929
- The power tool's drawing that
billet out like it's nothing.

08:32.929 --> 08:34.848
<i>- I want to take it</i>
<i>a little bit past</i>

08:34.848 --> 08:37.517
the length that I need because
I welded up the end of it.

08:37.517 --> 08:39.728
I got to get rid of that.

08:39.728 --> 08:42.480
<i>I want to hot cut that piece</i>
<i>of the end of it,</i>

08:42.480 --> 08:45.150
<i>so that I've got just clean,</i>
<i>pure Damascus to work with.</i>

08:45.150 --> 08:47.110
<i>I'm not using the chop saw,</i>

08:47.110 --> 08:49.112
<i>because I don't want that</i>
<i>billet to be cooling down,</i>

08:49.112 --> 08:50.697
<i>because that's another</i>
<i>loss of time.</i>

08:50.697 --> 08:52.741
<i>I want to get that piece</i>
<i>cut off there</i>

08:52.741 --> 08:54.200
<i>as fast as I can,</i>
<i>and get that piece</i>

08:54.200 --> 08:56.077
<i>back into the furnace.</i>

08:56.077 --> 08:58.913
- It looks to me like Howard's
getting a little tired.

08:58.913 --> 09:01.750
I think we're seeing a
kind of hypnosis going on.

09:01.750 --> 09:03.626
<i>- This is a step that</i>
<i>should have just been done</i>

09:03.626 --> 09:06.671
in just a matter of minutes,
and it's just not working out.

09:06.671 --> 09:08.840
<i>All these little frustrations</i>

09:08.840 --> 09:10.467
<i>really add up</i>
<i>to a lot of time.</i>

09:10.467 --> 09:11.885
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:11.885 --> 09:13.553
- Ryan's starting
to work that steel

09:13.553 --> 09:15.513
a little bit on the cold side.

09:15.513 --> 09:17.432
<i>- I keep having</i>
<i>to remind myself,</i>

09:17.432 --> 09:20.268
<i>I need to keep it hot.</i>
<i>I need to keep it hot.</i>

09:20.268 --> 09:23.188
Because, in armor,
I work at colder temperatures.

09:23.188 --> 09:24.981
<i>We use sheet metal.</i>

09:24.981 --> 09:27.233
<i>It's a little less likely</i>
<i>to break.</i>

09:27.233 --> 09:29.069
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:29.069 --> 09:31.780
<i>Armorers have to</i>
<i>produce something that will</i>

09:31.780 --> 09:35.533
deflect weapons,
hold its structural integrity,

09:35.533 --> 09:37.202
and look good.

09:37.202 --> 09:40.288
<i>[rock music]</i>

09:40.288 --> 09:41.790
<i>- If I made</i>
<i>this blade at home,</i>

09:41.790 --> 09:43.374
<i>I would take</i>
<i>three or four days.</i>

09:43.374 --> 09:45.835
Not--not like this.

09:45.835 --> 09:48.922
So I set the forge weld,
and without thinking,

09:48.922 --> 09:50.840
<i>I just start to draw it out.</i>

09:50.840 --> 09:52.592
And then, I kind of
made a mistake.

09:52.592 --> 09:54.803
- Nicholas is making
a very long blade.

09:54.803 --> 09:56.805
- It's the goalie stick.
- Yeah, yeah.

09:56.805 --> 10:00.058
<i>- I drew it out a little</i>
<i>further than I wanted.</i>

10:00.058 --> 10:03.269
<i>I chopped the end off,</i>
<i>go right back to the fire,</i>

10:03.269 --> 10:05.563
and the clock
doesn't stop ticking.

10:05.563 --> 10:09.067
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:09.067 --> 10:10.610
<i>- I'm folding my billet over</i>

10:10.610 --> 10:12.570
<i>to increase</i>
<i>the strength of it.</i>

10:12.570 --> 10:14.781
It also helps
bring out the pattern.

10:14.781 --> 10:17.075
- So it looks like Jacob
has folded over

10:17.075 --> 10:19.911
his billet right there,
and now, he's trying to

10:19.911 --> 10:22.122
re-forge weld that
back together.

10:22.122 --> 10:24.457
- I'm feeling great
at this point,

10:24.457 --> 10:27.961
because I not only forge-weld
once, I forge-weld twice.

10:27.961 --> 10:29.796
I know it's solid.

10:29.796 --> 10:33.258
- It looks like Jacob
has set that second fold

10:33.258 --> 10:35.260
in his forge weld there.
Do you see that?

10:35.260 --> 10:37.220
- If he can pull this off,
that's pretty cool.

10:37.220 --> 10:41.057
<i>- So I'm feeling like</i>
<i>I could go for a third one.</i>

10:41.057 --> 10:42.600
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:42.600 --> 10:44.269
- [bleep]

10:44.269 --> 10:45.687
No!

10:45.687 --> 10:47.564
Completely goes undone.

10:47.564 --> 10:51.067
No!

10:51.067 --> 10:53.570
[bleep], [bleep], [bleep].

10:53.570 --> 10:56.033
- Oh, no.
- [bleep].

10:59.200 --> 11:01.327
- Jacob just went
to set his last weld,

11:01.327 --> 11:04.080
and it's all over the map.

11:04.080 --> 11:05.498
<i>What am I going to do?</i>

11:05.498 --> 11:07.458
I can't just draw it out
and do it again.

11:07.458 --> 11:09.085
- Uh-oh.

11:09.085 --> 11:11.462
<i>- So I do the mature thing,</i>

11:11.462 --> 11:13.882
<i>and I just</i>
<i>lop it off with the chop saw.</i>

11:13.882 --> 11:16.259
- Jacob has created
a little bit of trouble here.

11:16.259 --> 11:18.595
<i>- I got to really</i>
<i>pull it together.</i>

11:18.595 --> 11:20.346
- So he's just got to
flatten it up,

11:20.346 --> 11:22.140
draw it as long as he can.

11:22.140 --> 11:24.225
The big question is,
does he have enough steel?

11:24.225 --> 11:27.520
<i>[rock music]</i>

11:27.520 --> 11:29.606
<i>- I finally get that piece</i>
<i>cut off of there.</i>

11:29.606 --> 11:32.859
- I have never seen anyone in
this forge hammer like that.

11:32.859 --> 11:35.028
- It's planishing.

11:35.028 --> 11:38.114
- That's got to be an armorer's
technique right there, right?

11:38.114 --> 11:40.033
- I'm not sure that it's
a normal technique

11:40.033 --> 11:42.368
for a bladesmith
to planish out his piece

11:42.368 --> 11:44.495
before taking it to a grinder.

11:44.495 --> 11:47.999
<i>For an armorer, every piece</i>
<i>that we make is planished.</i>

11:47.999 --> 11:50.418
<i>What I enjoy about using</i>
<i>those kind of techniques,</i>

11:50.418 --> 11:52.921
is that they're historical,
and when you're done,

11:52.921 --> 11:55.423
the quality of the piece
is far greater

11:55.423 --> 11:56.758
than anything
that the power tools

11:56.758 --> 11:58.134
or a press will do for you.

11:58.134 --> 12:00.803
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:00.803 --> 12:05.391
- Historically, armorers were
a very prestigious guild.

12:05.391 --> 12:07.352
<i>If you looked like</i>
<i>your armorer</i>

12:07.352 --> 12:09.187
<i>knew what he was doing,</i>

12:09.187 --> 12:13.441
your opponents were going
to approach you differently.

12:13.441 --> 12:16.236
<i>If I can nail this heat treat,</i>
<i>I'm in good shape.</i>

12:16.236 --> 12:19.781
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:19.781 --> 12:25.161
I pull it out, and it's warped,
and not just a little.

12:25.161 --> 12:27.288
It's warped a long, long way.

12:27.288 --> 12:29.123
[sighs]

12:29.123 --> 12:31.501
<i>I got to do something</i>
<i>right now.</i>

12:31.501 --> 12:35.713
I remembered a trick that an
old auto body guy taught me

12:35.713 --> 12:37.340
<i>to straighten frames.</i>

12:37.340 --> 12:39.425
<i>Just heat it up,</i>
<i>and then you put water</i>

12:39.425 --> 12:42.178
on the part side,
and it cools faster,

12:42.178 --> 12:44.138
<i>so it pulls it back.</i>

12:44.138 --> 12:46.266
- What?

12:46.266 --> 12:48.184
- Looks like he's rapid cooling
to straighten that blade.

12:48.184 --> 12:49.894
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:49.894 --> 12:51.229
- Whew!

12:51.229 --> 12:53.106
Thank you,
Wally Ashbaker.

12:53.106 --> 12:56.567
- Armorers, you have 20 minutes
remaining in this round!

12:56.567 --> 12:58.611
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:58.611 --> 13:00.738
<i>- I'm feeling great now.</i>
<i>I have a pretty solid blade.</i>

13:00.738 --> 13:02.573
<i>I still need to heat treat.</i>

13:02.573 --> 13:04.158
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:04.158 --> 13:05.743
I pull it out--

13:05.743 --> 13:07.328
Aw, [bleep].

13:07.328 --> 13:10.373
<i>And it's got a warp in it.</i>

13:10.373 --> 13:13.126
You have this
critical few seconds

13:13.126 --> 13:15.461
to where the steel
is still a little malleable.

13:15.461 --> 13:17.588
<i>So I decide I'm going</i>
<i>to use these seconds.</i>

13:17.588 --> 13:19.257
<i>I throw it in the vice.</i>

13:19.257 --> 13:21.884
If I break it,
I'm eliminated, I'm done.

13:21.884 --> 13:23.428
- There you go, go to the vice.

13:23.428 --> 13:25.430
- Don't break, don't break,
don't break.

13:25.430 --> 13:28.391
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

13:28.391 --> 13:30.184
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:30.184 --> 13:32.020
I pushed it as far
as I was comfortable.

13:32.020 --> 13:33.896
- There you go.

13:33.896 --> 13:35.857
<i>- It still has a little warp,</i>

13:35.857 --> 13:38.067
but I think I have enough
material on that blade

13:38.067 --> 13:39.819
<i>to make it straight.</i>

13:39.819 --> 13:41.696
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:41.696 --> 13:43.948
<i>- In the time it took me</i>
<i>to lose my cool,</i>

13:43.948 --> 13:45.992
<i>I lost a lot of time.</i>

13:45.992 --> 13:48.411
I got to still draw it out
a few more inches.

13:48.411 --> 13:50.163
I still have to grind it.

13:50.163 --> 13:53.124
<i>I still have to heat treat</i>
<i>and quench it.</i>

13:53.124 --> 13:55.793
<i>I start feeling savage.</i>

13:55.793 --> 13:58.713
<i>[rock music]</i>

13:58.713 --> 14:05.511
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:05.511 --> 14:09.432
Oh, nothing bites,
I know it's good.

14:09.432 --> 14:11.768
My tang might be small,
but it's big enough for pins,

14:11.768 --> 14:13.561
<i>so it's big enough</i>
<i>for a knife.</i>

14:13.561 --> 14:15.772
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:15.772 --> 14:20.610
- Ten, nine, eight, seven, six,

14:20.610 --> 14:25.698
five, four, three, two, one.

14:25.698 --> 14:28.576
Bladesmiths, shut down your
machines, drop your tools.

14:28.576 --> 14:32.580
This first round
of competition is over.

14:32.580 --> 14:36.167
<i>- Time gets called.</i>
<i>I'm feeling pretty good.</i>

14:36.167 --> 14:39.170
And I suddenly realize
it's Judgment Day,

14:39.170 --> 14:41.631
and I'm about to have
my sins revealed.

14:41.631 --> 14:44.300
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:44.300 --> 14:46.594
- All right, armorers, in this
first round of competition,

14:46.594 --> 14:50.181
we asked you to create a
layered steel Damascus blade.

14:50.181 --> 14:51.849
Now it's time for the judges

14:51.849 --> 14:53.726
to take a closer look
at your work.

14:53.726 --> 14:56.854
Nicholas, please present
your blade to the judges.

14:56.854 --> 14:58.981
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:58.981 --> 15:01.150
<i>- The profile is very</i>
<i>well executed.</i>

15:01.150 --> 15:02.860
<i>But there's</i>
<i>a pretty significant warp</i>

15:02.860 --> 15:05.196
<i>in the back of the blade.</i>

15:05.196 --> 15:07.448
You can watch it seesaw.

15:07.448 --> 15:10.952
<i>And there's a crack on the</i>
<i>back of the blade right here.</i>

15:10.952 --> 15:14.080
It runs about from here
to about there.

15:14.080 --> 15:16.207
If you move forward,
it would be nice to see

15:16.207 --> 15:18.960
how you deal with that.
- Ryan, you're up.

15:18.960 --> 15:20.670
Please present your blade
to the judges.

15:20.670 --> 15:22.380
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:22.380 --> 15:24.132
<i>- Your welds look solid.</i>

15:24.132 --> 15:26.050
<i>It's a nice piece of steel</i>
<i>you got here.</i>

15:26.050 --> 15:29.887
<i>I like the idea of the</i>
<i>integral bolster and pommel.</i>

15:29.887 --> 15:32.473
There's no problems
with delamination or cracking.

15:32.473 --> 15:35.101
My major concern with this
is the tang here.

15:35.101 --> 15:36.477
I don't know how
it's going to bulk out

15:36.477 --> 15:38.354
to be a comfortable handle,

15:38.354 --> 15:40.356
because we're going
to be chopping stuff with it,

15:40.356 --> 15:43.276
so it needs to have something
to connect me to the knife.

15:43.276 --> 15:45.570
- Howard, you're up next.

15:45.570 --> 15:47.572
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:47.572 --> 15:49.490
<i>- There's a lot</i>
<i>of material here.</i>

15:49.490 --> 15:51.367
<i>It's like a log-splitter.</i>

15:51.367 --> 15:53.786
[tapping on blade]

15:53.786 --> 15:55.872
There's kind of
a big flake up here.

15:55.872 --> 15:57.415
<i>I can see the seam</i>

15:57.415 --> 15:58.916
<i>run kind of all the way</i>
<i>around it,</i>

15:58.916 --> 16:00.585
<i>and I can</i>
<i>get a finger under it.</i>

16:00.585 --> 16:03.546
But what I do like is that
other than that piece

16:03.546 --> 16:06.340
up here in the front,
and a minor delam here,

16:06.340 --> 16:09.552
it looks solid to me.
- Jacob, you're up.

16:09.552 --> 16:11.053
Please present your blade
to the judges.

16:11.053 --> 16:13.389
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:13.389 --> 16:15.141
- All right, Jacob,
your struggles out there

16:15.141 --> 16:16.893
are definitely seen
on the blade.

16:16.893 --> 16:19.979
<i>Your edge is all over.</i>
<i>The spine is warped.</i>

16:19.979 --> 16:22.356
A lot of issues that
you have to fix over here.

16:22.356 --> 16:25.193
Especially where the tang
meets the blade.

16:25.193 --> 16:27.111
- I kind of saw you
getting into panic mode,

16:27.111 --> 16:29.113
like, I need to put a tang
on there, quick.

16:29.113 --> 16:31.157
And in doing that,
you pinched it

16:31.157 --> 16:34.076
right at the tang transition,
which is where

16:34.076 --> 16:36.787
all of the stress in a chopper
is going to come.

16:36.787 --> 16:39.165
This area right here,
it'll snap.

16:39.165 --> 16:40.708
I mean, there's no doubt
in my mind.

16:40.708 --> 16:44.253
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:44.253 --> 16:47.381
- The judges have made
their final decision, armorers.

16:47.381 --> 16:49.634
The person
leaving The Forge is...

16:49.634 --> 16:52.762
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

16:52.762 --> 16:56.474
Jacob, your blade
didn't make the cut.

16:56.474 --> 16:59.101
- Jacob, we watched you
struggle and fight your metal

16:59.101 --> 17:00.937
till the very end.

17:00.937 --> 17:03.522
But where others have failed,
you succeeded

17:03.522 --> 17:05.441
in finishing,
and turning something in.

17:05.441 --> 17:08.194
And for that, we commend you,
but at the end of the day,

17:08.194 --> 17:10.196
your blade is
the least finished of all.

17:10.196 --> 17:12.490
And for that,
we're sending you home.

17:12.490 --> 17:14.533
- Jacob, please surrender
your blade.

17:14.533 --> 17:16.202
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:16.202 --> 17:17.536
- I'm bummed.
I'm definitely bummed.

17:17.536 --> 17:19.664
But I had a great time.

17:19.664 --> 17:23.584
<i>First thing I do when I get</i>
<i>home is say hi to my cat.</i>

17:23.584 --> 17:24.627
Mittens would be proud.

17:24.627 --> 17:25.836
[laughs]

17:25.836 --> 17:28.923
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:28.923 --> 17:30.967
- All right, armorers,
congratulations.

17:30.967 --> 17:32.260
Your work has landed you
in the second round

17:32.260 --> 17:33.803
of this competition,

17:33.803 --> 17:35.638
and now that your blades
have been tempered,

17:35.638 --> 17:37.431
it's time to turn them
into fully functional weapons

17:37.431 --> 17:39.809
by attaching handles to them
so that we can test them

17:39.809 --> 17:43.563
for strength and durability
in a helmet chop,

17:43.563 --> 17:46.566
and for edge retention
in a quilted armor slice.

17:46.566 --> 17:49.944
Good luck, armorers.
Your three hours starts now.

17:49.944 --> 17:52.947
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

17:52.947 --> 17:55.157
- There we go.
Howard to the grinder.

17:55.157 --> 17:57.493
<i>- I had some inclusions</i>
<i>on the curve</i>

17:57.493 --> 17:59.495
<i>coming down</i>
<i>to the edge of the blade.</i>

17:59.495 --> 18:01.372
<i>I left enough material</i>
<i>so I can grind those</i>

18:01.372 --> 18:02.999
<i>out of the blade,</i>

18:02.999 --> 18:04.584
and that will also help
lighten it up.

18:07.336 --> 18:09.755
<i>In the pantry, there's</i>
<i>lots and lots of choices.</i>

18:09.755 --> 18:11.716
But I want to keep it simple.

18:11.716 --> 18:13.175
<i>The maple pieces</i>

18:13.175 --> 18:15.094
that I've chosen,
they're very consistent.

18:15.094 --> 18:16.679
<i>One's not thicker</i>
<i>than the other.</i>

18:16.679 --> 18:18.306
So that'll make my job
a lot easier.

18:18.306 --> 18:20.182
<i>[rock music]</i>

18:20.182 --> 18:22.977
- My game plan is,
got to fix the warp.

18:22.977 --> 18:24.520
- What is Nicholas doing now?

18:24.520 --> 18:27.064
- He's making
a three-bar bending jig.

18:27.064 --> 18:29.734
<i>- Grab a piece of rebar,</i>
<i>cut three chunks off,</i>

18:29.734 --> 18:32.445
<i>put the knife in the vice,</i>
<i>and my three pins.</i>

18:32.445 --> 18:35.906
- It's not often that a smith
actually pulls off this jig.

18:35.906 --> 18:38.826
I think we've seen it done
successfully maybe twice.

18:38.826 --> 18:40.328
- Let's hope for three.

18:40.328 --> 18:42.163
<i>- I hope it doesn't break.</i>

18:42.163 --> 18:45.333
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:45.333 --> 18:48.085
I can grind that.

18:48.085 --> 18:50.296
- I need to get some holes
drilled in this tang.

18:50.296 --> 18:53.758
Wow, that spot is hard.
Holy crap.

18:53.758 --> 18:56.636
<i>I get about halfway through</i>
<i>the blade--</i>

18:56.636 --> 18:58.596
[metal clangs]
[bleep]

18:58.596 --> 19:01.891
My bit breaks.
My blade's just too hard.

19:01.891 --> 19:03.976
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:03.976 --> 19:06.312
<i>Now I have to go back</i>
<i>and soften the tang,</i>

19:06.312 --> 19:07.938
<i>which takes more time.</i>

19:07.938 --> 19:10.983
Come on, baby.
- One hour has elapsed.

19:10.983 --> 19:13.152
You have just
two hours remaining

19:13.152 --> 19:15.863
until we test your blades.

19:15.863 --> 19:18.115
<i>I want to go ahead</i>
<i>and acid the edge now.</i>

19:18.115 --> 19:20.409
See if there's
any other issues in my blade,

19:20.409 --> 19:23.079
because the acid would then
bring that out right away.

19:23.079 --> 19:26.082
<i>But I can't get the top</i>
<i>off of this acid bath.</i>

19:26.082 --> 19:28.376
- Use your man hands!

19:28.376 --> 19:30.503
- When the pressure is on,
the simplest things

19:30.503 --> 19:32.546
can really
frustrate you, quick.

19:32.546 --> 19:35.132
That's when you got to step
back and look at other options.

19:35.132 --> 19:37.051
<i>[rock music]</i>

19:37.051 --> 19:38.260
- Ah, there you go.

19:38.260 --> 19:40.429
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:40.429 --> 19:44.392
- My blade came out as I had
designed it, and it looks good.

19:44.392 --> 19:46.060
I'm ready to move on
to the scales.

19:46.060 --> 19:47.436
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:47.436 --> 19:49.647
<i>- I've got my layers glued up.</i>

19:49.647 --> 19:51.232
<i>I've got my pins in.</i>

19:51.232 --> 19:52.733
There we go.

19:52.733 --> 19:54.443
I'm happy, and now,
I just got to wait

19:54.443 --> 19:56.737
for five minutes to go by.

19:56.737 --> 19:59.031
- Now, Nicholas has to wait.

19:59.031 --> 20:01.575
- Waiting on the forge floor
is the hardest.

20:01.575 --> 20:03.828
<i>I'm watching the minutes</i>
<i>count down,</i>

20:03.828 --> 20:05.705
and there's nothing I can do.

20:05.705 --> 20:07.665
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:07.665 --> 20:11.001
- I get through the little
trials at the drill press,

20:11.001 --> 20:12.461
<i>so now, I have to</i>
<i>get my handle done.</i>

20:12.461 --> 20:14.171
Okay.

20:14.171 --> 20:17.258
<i>I need to carve</i>
<i>the shape of my tang out</i>

20:17.258 --> 20:20.594
so that these scales come
together and match up smoothly.

20:20.594 --> 20:23.931
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:23.931 --> 20:26.600
- He's trying to burn
his handle material

20:26.600 --> 20:29.228
around his tang.

20:29.228 --> 20:30.855
- I think that's
the slowest way

20:30.855 --> 20:32.565
I could imagine ever trying.

20:32.565 --> 20:34.817
Go get a rotary tool
and just burn it out.

20:34.817 --> 20:36.527
You could get the wood chisels.

20:36.527 --> 20:40.281
- I'm trying my burn-in,
and it's doing bugger-all.

20:40.281 --> 20:42.700
- I've seen the burn-throughs
for putting it through,

20:42.700 --> 20:45.870
but doing what he's doing?
I don't get it.

20:45.870 --> 20:47.776
- There's a fire,
there's a fire.

20:51.917 --> 20:55.129
- I'm trying my burn-in,
and it's doing bugger-all.
- I'm realiz

20:55.129 --> 20:58.174
<i>I'm realizing</i>
<i>I've approached this</i>

20:58.174 --> 21:00.050
<i>from a bad perspective.</i>

21:00.050 --> 21:01.886
That's not
going to work for me.

21:01.886 --> 21:05.389
Now, I'm back to
grinding some out,

21:05.389 --> 21:08.225
<i>and hoping I get there fast.</i>

21:08.225 --> 21:12.855
- Armorers, you got 45 minutes
left on the clock.

21:12.855 --> 21:14.857
<i>- I left the back half</i>
<i>of my blade</i>

21:14.857 --> 21:18.444
<i>a little less sharp to hold up</i>
<i>against the helmet chop.</i>

21:18.444 --> 21:20.529
But yet, I've still got
a good six inches

21:20.529 --> 21:22.323
of cutting edge
on the front of it.

21:22.323 --> 21:25.159
<i>And hopefully,</i>
<i>when they test the chop on it,</i>

21:25.159 --> 21:27.912
<i>it'll hold up to that impact</i>
<i>on the steel.</i>

21:27.912 --> 21:30.456
<i>The decision I made to</i>
<i>engineer my blade this way</i>

21:30.456 --> 21:31.999
can make or break me.

21:31.999 --> 21:33.834
<i>[rock music]</i>

21:33.834 --> 21:35.377
<i>- The pattern of my blade</i>

21:35.377 --> 21:37.671
turned out like
kind of a wavy W pattern.

21:37.671 --> 21:39.465
I'm pretty happy with it.

21:39.465 --> 21:42.134
- Nicholas brought a rod-guided
sharpening system

21:42.134 --> 21:43.969
that gets you
very precise angles.

21:43.969 --> 21:45.471
You can get a very,
very good sharpening with it,

21:45.471 --> 21:47.598
but it takes a very long time.

21:47.598 --> 21:51.310
- I usually take two or three
hours to get a knife sharpened.

21:51.310 --> 21:52.686
- Ten minutes!

21:52.686 --> 21:54.313
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

21:54.313 --> 21:57.107
<i>- I finally got through</i>
<i>this wood.</i>

21:57.107 --> 21:58.818
<i>Now, the epoxy's set,</i>

21:58.818 --> 22:01.529
and I have to turn
these two clunky scales

22:01.529 --> 22:03.948
<i>into a handle.</i>

22:03.948 --> 22:06.826
- It looks like he's
in absolute panic mode.

22:06.826 --> 22:10.204
<i>- While I'm panicking,</i>
<i>I mess up.</i>

22:10.204 --> 22:14.333
I have pulled too much wood
away down by my pinkie.

22:14.333 --> 22:17.086
<i>There's really no time</i>
<i>to fix this.</i>

22:17.086 --> 22:19.547
If everybody's blades
perform well,

22:19.547 --> 22:21.549
that could be
what sends me home.

22:21.549 --> 22:26.428
- Five, four, three, two, one.

22:26.428 --> 22:30.516
Armorers, this round
of competition is over.

22:30.516 --> 22:32.268
- [exhales]

22:32.268 --> 22:35.396
<i>- At this stage,</i>
<i>it's in the judges' hands.</i>

22:35.396 --> 22:37.815
<i>We'll see what happens.</i>

22:37.815 --> 22:40.943
- Armorers,
this is the strength test.

22:40.943 --> 22:43.070
To test the strength and
durability of your edges,

22:43.070 --> 22:44.947
as well as the overall
construction of your knives,

22:44.947 --> 22:47.741
I will be mercilessly
hacking and bashing your knives

22:47.741 --> 22:49.034
into these helmets.

22:49.034 --> 22:50.494
Remember,
this test is all about

22:50.494 --> 22:52.037
what the helmets do
to your knives,

22:52.037 --> 22:54.123
and not what the knives
do to the helmets.

22:54.123 --> 22:56.166
Nicholas, you're up first.
You ready?

22:56.166 --> 22:57.293
- Let's do this.

22:57.293 --> 22:59.003
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:59.003 --> 23:01.255
<i>- There's so many things</i>
<i>that can go wrong.</i>

23:01.255 --> 23:03.549
<i>It could shatter,</i>
<i>it could splinter.</i>

23:03.549 --> 23:05.134
Hopefully, it doesn't break.

23:05.134 --> 23:08.095
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

23:08.095 --> 23:09.471
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:09.471 --> 23:12.433
<i>[rock music]</i>

23:12.433 --> 23:19.398
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:22.568 --> 23:24.069
- Nice.

23:24.069 --> 23:25.905
<i>[tense music]</i>

23:25.905 --> 23:28.073
- Well, Nicholas, your edge
held up pretty well.

23:28.073 --> 23:29.617
- Phew.

23:29.617 --> 23:31.535
- The thing I don't like
is this handle.

23:31.535 --> 23:34.788
It is so small,
that it's rocking in my hand

23:34.788 --> 23:36.373
as I'm trying
to hold the thing.

23:36.373 --> 23:38.876
But all in all,
it held up very well.

23:38.876 --> 23:40.294
- Thank you.

23:40.294 --> 23:41.587
- Ryan, you're up.
You ready?

23:41.587 --> 23:43.339
- As ready as I'll ever be.

23:43.339 --> 23:46.300
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

23:46.300 --> 23:51.972
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:51.972 --> 23:54.892
<i>[rock music]</i>

23:54.892 --> 24:01.899
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:03.943 --> 24:06.737
<i>[tense music]</i>

24:06.737 --> 24:09.990
- Well, Ryan, there's
some rolling on the edge.

24:09.990 --> 24:12.242
For the most part,
it held up fine.

24:12.242 --> 24:16.246
But man, this handle.
Oh, I do not like this handle.

24:16.246 --> 24:17.915
It was rolling
all over the place.

24:17.915 --> 24:21.210
But all in all, it held up.
Well done.

24:21.210 --> 24:23.128
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:23.128 --> 24:24.463
Howard, you're up.
You ready?

24:24.463 --> 24:25.589
- I'm ready.

24:25.589 --> 24:28.550
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

24:28.550 --> 24:34.473
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:34.473 --> 24:37.393
<i>[rock music]</i>

24:37.393 --> 24:44.358
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:46.860 --> 24:48.737
<i>[tense music]</i>

24:48.737 --> 24:53.117
- Well, Howard, this is still
a really heavy knife.

24:53.117 --> 24:57.621
Where I was hitting the helmet,
it's not sharp.

24:57.621 --> 24:59.540
I don't know if that
was the helmet,

24:59.540 --> 25:01.625
or it was never sharp,

25:01.625 --> 25:03.419
but it's certainly
not sharp now.

25:03.419 --> 25:06.005
But it's still
all in one piece,

25:06.005 --> 25:08.007
so we'll see how it does
in the sharpness test.

25:08.007 --> 25:09.425
- Thank you.

25:11.760 --> 25:15.556
- Armorers,
welcome to the sharpness test.

25:15.556 --> 25:17.766
To see if there's
any edge left on your weapon,

25:17.766 --> 25:20.227
I will slice across
this quilted armor.

25:20.227 --> 25:22.271
Quilted armor
can absorb impact,

25:22.271 --> 25:25.441
so you'll need a sharp edge
to cut right through them.

25:25.441 --> 25:27.151
Nicholas, you're up first.
You ready?

25:27.151 --> 25:28.527
- I'm ready.
Let's do this.

25:28.527 --> 25:31.488
<i>[tense music]</i>

25:31.488 --> 25:34.116
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:34.116 --> 25:37.036
<i>[rock music]</i>

25:37.036 --> 25:41.540
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:41.540 --> 25:43.917
<i>[tense music]</i>

25:43.917 --> 25:46.420
- Nice.
- All right, Nicholas.

25:46.420 --> 25:48.422
First up, it's got
a nice balance to it.

25:48.422 --> 25:50.549
Definitely a forward chopper.

25:50.549 --> 25:53.052
The handle's a little bit
on the smaller side,

25:53.052 --> 25:55.554
but it will cut.
- Thank you.

25:55.554 --> 25:56.722
- All right, Ryan,
you're up next.

25:56.722 --> 25:58.348
- You ready?
- I'm ready.

25:58.348 --> 26:01.310
<i>[tense music]</i>

26:01.310 --> 26:05.064
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:05.064 --> 26:08.067
<i>[rock music]</i>

26:08.067 --> 26:12.905
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:12.905 --> 26:14.323
<i>[tense music]</i>

26:14.323 --> 26:15.824
- Okay, Ryan.

26:15.824 --> 26:18.535
I like the combat feel
of this blade.

26:18.535 --> 26:21.163
There is a little bit of the
slight roundedness right there,

26:21.163 --> 26:22.623
on the bottom of the handle.

26:22.623 --> 26:24.333
But your edge here
is sharp enough

26:24.333 --> 26:27.002
to cut through the quilted
armor, and it will cut.

26:27.002 --> 26:28.629
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:28.629 --> 26:30.005
All right, Howard,
it's your turn.

26:30.005 --> 26:32.674
You ready?
- Yes, I am.

26:32.674 --> 26:35.344
I didn't really design
my blade as well

26:35.344 --> 26:37.471
for the sharpness test.

26:37.471 --> 26:39.431
<i>I put everything into</i>
<i>leaving the back half</i>

26:39.431 --> 26:41.558
<i>heavier than the front.</i>

26:41.558 --> 26:43.018
This is the moment of truth.

26:43.018 --> 26:45.304
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:49.858 --> 26:56.782
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:59.993 --> 27:02.204
- Well, Howard, we have
some issues over here.

27:02.204 --> 27:03.872
I can run my hand through this.

27:03.872 --> 27:05.624
It's very stout.
It's not sharp.

27:05.624 --> 27:09.586
This is an unsharpened edge.
It will not cut.

27:09.586 --> 27:11.588
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

27:11.588 --> 27:14.216
- Armorers, it's time for one
of you to leave The Forge.

27:14.216 --> 27:19.471
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:19.471 --> 27:21.098
Howard.

27:21.098 --> 27:23.058
Your blade
did not make the cut.

27:23.058 --> 27:25.477
- Howard,
in the sharpness test,

27:25.477 --> 27:27.813
<i>your edged weapon didn't cut.</i>

27:27.813 --> 27:29.940
And for that reason,
we're sending you home.

27:29.940 --> 27:32.651
- Howard,
please surrender your work.

27:32.651 --> 27:33.986
♪ ♪

27:33.986 --> 27:35.612
<i>- My blade just didn't cut,</i>

27:35.612 --> 27:38.699
and a blade that doesn't cut
is just a club.

27:38.699 --> 27:40.742
<i>Probably should have changed</i>
<i>my strategy a little bit,</i>

27:40.742 --> 27:43.537
and sharpened it
another layer lower.

27:43.537 --> 27:45.455
<i>I definitely feel like</i>
<i>I did a good job</i>

27:45.455 --> 27:47.374
<i>in representing the armorers.</i>

27:47.374 --> 27:48.709
Armorers definitely
are the most versatile

27:48.709 --> 27:50.752
in uh, metalcrafts.

27:50.752 --> 27:54.381
<i>The one thing I do have to say</i>
<i>to Nicholas and Ryan,</i>

27:54.381 --> 27:56.425
do your best, because you're
representing everyone now.

27:56.425 --> 28:01.013
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:01.013 --> 28:03.974
- Nicholas, Ryan,
we're still searching

28:03.974 --> 28:06.643
for our armorer that's going
to occupy that anvil

28:06.643 --> 28:08.437
at the Tournament of Champions.

28:08.437 --> 28:10.105
And now, we're sending you
back to your home forges

28:10.105 --> 28:12.649
to re-create
an iconic weapon from history.

28:12.649 --> 28:14.443
That weapon is...

28:14.443 --> 28:17.446
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

28:17.446 --> 28:18.989
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:18.989 --> 28:20.449
The hooded katar.

28:20.449 --> 28:22.784
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:22.784 --> 28:25.996
<i>Emerging in South India</i>
<i>around the 16th century,</i>

28:25.996 --> 28:28.415
<i>the hooded katar was a favored</i>
<i>close combat weapon</i>

28:28.415 --> 28:31.335
<i>that actually predated</i>
<i>the classic hoodless katar.</i>

28:31.335 --> 28:33.170
<i>The hood of the hooded katar</i>
<i>was designed</i>

28:33.170 --> 28:35.339
<i>to protect the user's</i>
<i>hand and wrist.</i>

28:35.339 --> 28:38.008
<i>The blade's unique handle was</i>
<i>designed for a punching motion</i>

28:38.008 --> 28:39.676
<i>which delivered forceful blows</i>

28:39.676 --> 28:42.471
<i>that could pierce armor</i>
<i>or chainmail.</i>

28:42.471 --> 28:44.723
<i>The katar didn't just see</i>
<i>action on the battlefield</i>

28:44.723 --> 28:46.767
<i>as Mughal nobility</i>
<i>would often take</i>

28:46.767 --> 28:49.311
<i>pairs of katars</i>
<i>on tiger hunts.</i>

28:49.311 --> 28:52.397
<i>While the weapon faded</i>
<i>from use in the 19th century,</i>

28:52.397 --> 28:54.358
<i>it is still featured in the</i>
<i>"Soulcalibur" video games</i>

28:54.358 --> 28:56.526
<i>as the favored weapon</i>
<i>of Voldo.</i>

28:56.526 --> 28:58.445
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:58.445 --> 29:01.073
Your blades must fall within
the following parameters.

29:01.073 --> 29:03.825
It must be double-edged.
It must have a hooded guard

29:03.825 --> 29:06.536
that completely
covers the hand.

29:06.536 --> 29:08.622
Armorers, you'll have five days
at your home forges

29:08.622 --> 29:10.540
to complete this challenge.

29:10.540 --> 29:12.334
At the end of those five days,
you're going to return,

29:12.334 --> 29:13.752
and you're going
to present those weapons

29:13.752 --> 29:15.462
to our panel of expert judges.

29:15.462 --> 29:17.589
After they've tested
and examined them,

29:17.589 --> 29:20.258
they'll declare one of you
the armorer class

29:20.258 --> 29:21.677
"Forged in Fire" champion,

29:21.677 --> 29:23.095
who gets the opportunity
to move on

29:23.095 --> 29:24.846
to our Tournament of Champions.

29:24.846 --> 29:27.516
Good luck, armorers.
We'll see you in five days.

29:29.476 --> 29:31.895
<i>[tense music]</i>

29:31.895 --> 29:35.357
<i>- It's really nice to be</i>
<i>back here in my forge,</i>

29:35.357 --> 29:37.109
<i>in my element.</i>

29:37.109 --> 29:40.112
<i>I'm excited to see</i>
<i>Nicholas's blade.</i>

29:40.112 --> 29:42.239
I'm really excited to see
how mine beats it.

29:42.239 --> 29:45.158
All right.
Here goes something.

29:45.158 --> 29:46.868
<i>[rock music]</i>

29:46.868 --> 29:49.705
I am going to attempt
making my blade

29:49.705 --> 29:51.581
<i>and the bars</i>
<i>that go down the arm</i>

29:51.581 --> 29:54.710
all out of one
contiguous piece.

29:54.710 --> 29:58.213
Because, end result,
I think it will be stronger.

29:58.213 --> 30:00.757
<i>I have to be really careful</i>
<i>about this.</i>

30:00.757 --> 30:02.718
[bleep].

30:02.718 --> 30:05.762
<i>[rock music]</i>

30:05.762 --> 30:07.180
- Happy to be home,
getting ready

30:07.180 --> 30:09.057
to start working
at my own forge.

30:09.057 --> 30:10.475
<i>I'd like to get</i>
<i>a Damascus billet made.</i>

30:10.475 --> 30:13.103
Damascus is
the traditional steel

30:13.103 --> 30:14.646
<i>that the katar</i>
<i>would be made out of,</i>

30:14.646 --> 30:16.606
so I want to stay
in that traditional style.

30:16.606 --> 30:20.152
Shiny is nice,
but Damascus is sexy as hell.

30:20.152 --> 30:21.695
<i>By the end of today,</i>
<i>I would like to have</i>

30:21.695 --> 30:24.072
<i>the Damascus</i>
<i>for my blade finished.</i>

30:24.072 --> 30:26.616
<i>So I'm getting closer</i>
<i>to the end of day one,</i>

30:26.616 --> 30:28.368
and I've got a little bit
of a cold shut.

30:28.368 --> 30:29.786
So I think I'm going
to spend the rest of the time

30:29.786 --> 30:31.496
grinding out that cancer,

30:31.496 --> 30:33.749
so tomorrow, I can make it
into a knife blade.

30:33.749 --> 30:36.668
<i>[rock music]</i>

30:36.668 --> 30:38.795
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:38.795 --> 30:41.465
Starting over.

30:41.465 --> 30:43.341
<i>I got a cold shut that goes</i>

30:43.341 --> 30:44.259
<i>all the way</i>
<i>through the billet.</i>

30:44.259 --> 30:45.761
So this is a setback.

30:45.761 --> 30:47.429
I have four and a half
hours invested

30:47.429 --> 30:49.598
<i>in a Damascus billet</i>
<i>that I can't use.</i>

30:49.598 --> 30:51.433
So I think it would be safer
to start over.

30:51.433 --> 30:53.268
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:53.268 --> 30:55.604
Son of a [bleep].
What am I going to do?

30:55.604 --> 30:57.731
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:57.731 --> 31:01.443
<i>- So it's day three.</i>
<i>I feel great about my blade.</i>

31:01.443 --> 31:04.154
It has a chopping blade
that should resist

31:04.154 --> 31:07.699
against bone
or coconuts or ice,

31:07.699 --> 31:11.119
and do really well on that
while still retaining its edge.

31:11.119 --> 31:15.582
And now, onto the hood
of the hooded katar.

31:15.582 --> 31:17.584
This is where being an armorer

31:17.584 --> 31:19.920
really starts to
come into this project.

31:19.920 --> 31:23.965
<i>I'm using the stake as,</i>
<i>essentially, my anvil.</i>

31:23.965 --> 31:28.553
<i>Making this hood, really,</i>
<i>is the armorer's skillset.</i>

31:28.553 --> 31:32.224
<i>It's my playground.</i>
<i>This is my court.</i>

31:32.224 --> 31:33.934
<i>This is where</i>
<i>I'm going to shine.</i>

31:33.934 --> 31:36.228
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:36.228 --> 31:38.522
<i>- It's the start of day three.</i>
<i>I really feel caught up.</i>

31:38.522 --> 31:40.524
<i>Katar is</i>
<i>a rather strange shape.</i>

31:40.524 --> 31:42.776
It doesn't fit
in my quench tank.

31:42.776 --> 31:45.320
<i>I have a big-ass flower pot.</i>
<i>I think that might work.</i>

31:45.320 --> 31:46.988
[bleep]

31:46.988 --> 31:48.865
That's exactly
what I didn't want to do!

31:48.865 --> 31:51.409
I really need my heat treat
to go right.

31:51.409 --> 31:53.912
I make a mad dash,
and shove it in the flower pot.

31:53.912 --> 31:55.997
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:55.997 --> 31:57.999
[metal scrapes]

31:57.999 --> 32:00.293
That's the sound
I want to hear.

32:00.293 --> 32:03.213
<i>So I'm going to make a pattern</i>
<i>for the hood, for the guard.</i>

32:03.213 --> 32:05.382
<i>I'm going to cut some</i>
<i>sheet metal a little big,</i>

32:05.382 --> 32:07.843
<i>because I'm not exactly sure</i>
<i>where this is going to go.</i>

32:07.843 --> 32:10.637
<i>End of day three,</i>
<i>I got a few minutes left.</i>

32:10.637 --> 32:13.682
I'm tired, my arms hurt.
I need a beer.

32:13.682 --> 32:15.475
<i>[rock music]</i>

32:15.475 --> 32:17.477
- Today, I've worked
a little time in

32:17.477 --> 32:20.063
for some added embellishments
that'll pretty it up,

32:20.063 --> 32:23.358
<i>but I don't have to</i>
<i>put these on.</i>

32:23.358 --> 32:25.485
My hammer work
came out really nice.

32:25.485 --> 32:27.070
<i>Now that I've got that done,</i>

32:27.070 --> 32:29.698
I'm going to put
my coloring in.

32:29.698 --> 32:33.410
<i>My copper leaf element will be</i>

32:33.410 --> 32:36.538
the major eye catch
of this overall weapon.

32:36.538 --> 32:38.081
We're going to heat it up,

32:38.081 --> 32:40.667
and give a really nice
enameled finish.

32:40.667 --> 32:42.586
<i>[rock music]</i>

32:42.586 --> 32:45.422
- [indistinct]

32:45.422 --> 32:47.132
- Yes, I'd love some coffee.

32:47.132 --> 32:48.258
[gasps]

32:48.258 --> 32:50.427
Oh, bugger.

32:50.427 --> 32:51.197
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

32:55.432 --> 32:57.767
- Oh, bugger.
<i>I burned a hole</i>
<i>in my</i>

32:57.767 --> 33:00.937
<i>I just burned away</i>
<i>a big hole in my copper,</i>

33:00.937 --> 33:02.606
<i>and so now,</i>
<i>I need to cover it up,</i>

33:02.606 --> 33:05.525
<i>or the whole process</i>
<i>was a waste.</i>

33:05.525 --> 33:08.320
<i>So this brass piece,</i>
<i>I will put two holes</i>

33:08.320 --> 33:10.614
<i>through this from</i>
<i>the inside of the hood</i>

33:10.614 --> 33:15.118
<i>so it rolls over the end</i>
<i>of this that's burned off,</i>

33:15.118 --> 33:16.995
and I'm pretty sure we're fine.

33:16.995 --> 33:18.997
[sighs]

33:18.997 --> 33:20.916
<i>[rock music]</i>

33:20.916 --> 33:22.834
<i>- It's the last day.</i>

33:22.834 --> 33:24.461
<i>I have a little polishing,</i>
<i>a little blackening.</i>

33:24.461 --> 33:27.255
A little etching,
and a little assembly.

33:27.255 --> 33:29.591
And then, I'll sharpen
the blade, and I'm done.

33:29.591 --> 33:31.509
<i>Down the blade,</i>
<i>I'm going to write</i>

33:31.509 --> 33:33.553
<i>"Forged in Fire" in Hindi,</i>
<i>and on the guard,</i>

33:33.553 --> 33:35.263
<i>I'm going to have the names</i>

33:35.263 --> 33:37.557
<i>of all my competitors</i>
<i>in Hindi, too.</i>

33:37.557 --> 33:40.644
<i>Blackening stuff is terrible</i>
<i>in this chemical process.</i>

33:40.644 --> 33:42.854
<i>It smells like rotten eggs.</i>

33:42.854 --> 33:45.273
It just makes you
want to puke.

33:45.273 --> 33:48.151
<i>[rock music]</i>

33:48.151 --> 33:49.527
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:49.527 --> 33:51.738
Pow!

33:51.738 --> 33:54.449
Well, parts come off,
and so I think it's working.

33:54.449 --> 33:57.452
Yeah, yeah.

33:57.452 --> 33:59.537
I made a good katar.

33:59.537 --> 34:02.499
<i>[tense music]</i>

34:02.499 --> 34:04.125
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:04.125 --> 34:06.294
- Nicholas, Ryan,
welcome back to the Forge.

34:06.294 --> 34:09.214
You armorers have had five days
at your home forges

34:09.214 --> 34:12.425
to work on finale weapons.
What's on the line?

34:12.425 --> 34:16.388
$50,000, and that position
at the armorer's anvil

34:16.388 --> 34:18.265
in our Tournament of Champions.

34:18.265 --> 34:20.308
Now that your work is done,
why don't you

34:20.308 --> 34:22.435
tell the judges about it?
Nick, you're up first.

34:22.435 --> 34:23.687
- Um, I made the blade
out of 5160.

34:23.687 --> 34:25.730
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:25.730 --> 34:28.984
<i>The guard is 4130,</i>
<i>heat treated and blackened.</i>

34:28.984 --> 34:31.403
<i>The frame for the handle</i>
<i>is a Turkish twist,</i>

34:31.403 --> 34:33.738
<i>15N20, and 1095.</i>

34:33.738 --> 34:36.408
- Ryan, how'd it go for you
at your home forge?

34:36.408 --> 34:38.994
- I utilized 5160 for my blade.

34:38.994 --> 34:42.914
<i>The hood itself</i>
<i>is 4130 chromoly</i>

34:42.914 --> 34:44.833
<i>that's been blackened</i>
<i>and heat treated.</i>

34:44.833 --> 34:47.419
<i>And then, I've added</i>
<i>a copper embellishment</i>

34:47.419 --> 34:49.379
<i>for some of the accents.</i>

34:49.379 --> 34:50.839
- All right, gentleman.
Well, your weapons will now

34:50.839 --> 34:52.465
be put through
a series of three tests.

34:52.465 --> 34:54.801
A strength test,
a sharpness test,

34:54.801 --> 34:57.512
and up first, the kill test.
Doug?

34:57.512 --> 34:59.806
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

34:59.806 --> 35:02.684
- Armorers, I've been
looking forward to this.

35:02.684 --> 35:06.146
The hooded katar, it's the
big daddy of punch daggers.

35:06.146 --> 35:08.648
To find out what kind of lethal
damage your weapon will do,

35:08.648 --> 35:10.817
I will take your weapon
and deliver thrusts and slashes

35:10.817 --> 35:12.360
on this pig carcass.

35:12.360 --> 35:13.737
Nicholas, you're up first.
You ready?

35:13.737 --> 35:14.946
- Oh, yeah.
- Let's do this.

35:14.946 --> 35:16.656
- Nice.

35:16.656 --> 35:18.450
<i>Pig carcass.</i>

35:18.450 --> 35:20.619
Uh, I think it's just
going to destroy it.

35:20.619 --> 35:22.746
It's going to stab
right through that thing,

35:22.746 --> 35:26.499
and just chop it up into bits.

35:26.499 --> 35:29.377
<i>[rock music]</i>

35:29.377 --> 35:36.301
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:44.351 --> 35:46.436
<i>[tense music]</i>

35:46.436 --> 35:48.480
- All right, Nicholas, let's
talk about your hooded katar.

35:48.480 --> 35:51.358
First off, with the kind
of bounce it has,

35:51.358 --> 35:54.194
wherever I point,
it follows with the tip.

35:54.194 --> 35:57.238
On its slashing, well,
as you can see, pork chops.

35:57.238 --> 35:59.699
Your hooded katar will kill.

35:59.699 --> 36:01.451
- Nice.

36:01.451 --> 36:02.911
- All right, Ryan, your turn.
You ready?

36:02.911 --> 36:04.621
- Yeah.
- Let's do this.

36:04.621 --> 36:07.540
<i>[tense music]</i>

36:07.540 --> 36:14.547
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:14.547 --> 36:17.467
<i>[rock music]</i>

36:17.467 --> 36:24.432
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:29.521 --> 36:32.524
<i>[tense music]</i>

36:32.524 --> 36:34.734
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:34.734 --> 36:37.487
All right, Ryan, let's talk
about your hooded katar here.

36:37.487 --> 36:41.116
Your blade, it has
a very good form right here,

36:41.116 --> 36:43.993
and it went all the way
through the pig every time.

36:43.993 --> 36:46.788
But your edge,
it's not sharp enough

36:46.788 --> 36:48.581
to cut through the pig.

36:48.581 --> 36:51.167
But overall, because of
the lethal kind of thrusts

36:51.167 --> 36:53.670
that this will do
to any human body,

36:53.670 --> 36:56.089
your weapon will kill.

36:56.089 --> 37:00.635
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:00.635 --> 37:02.804
- Armorers, to test
the strength and durability

37:02.804 --> 37:04.597
of your edge, as well as
the overall construction

37:04.597 --> 37:07.517
of your katars, I'm going
to be stabbing and bashing

37:07.517 --> 37:10.019
into these suits of armor
and vambraces.

37:10.019 --> 37:11.396
Remember, this test
is all about

37:11.396 --> 37:13.189
what the armor
does to your katars,

37:13.189 --> 37:14.691
and not what the katar
does to the armor.

37:14.691 --> 37:16.151
Nicholas, you're up first.
You ready?

37:16.151 --> 37:17.444
- I'm ready.
Hit it hard.

37:17.444 --> 37:18.653
- No other way to do it.

37:18.653 --> 37:20.613
- [laughs]

37:20.613 --> 37:23.408
<i>[tense music]</i>

37:23.408 --> 37:24.826
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:24.826 --> 37:27.746
<i>[rock music]</i>

37:27.746 --> 37:34.586
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:39.883 --> 37:41.885
<i>[tense music]</i>

37:41.885 --> 37:43.678
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:43.678 --> 37:45.346
- Well, first things first,
Nicholas.

37:45.346 --> 37:47.724
There is a little bit
of glinting on the edge

37:47.724 --> 37:49.434
from contact with the armor.

37:49.434 --> 37:51.603
The hourglass shape
you have here,

37:51.603 --> 37:54.272
it was banging me here and on
the back of the wrist as well.

37:54.272 --> 37:57.525
But in general,
it held up really well.

37:57.525 --> 37:58.985
Well done.
- Thank you.

37:58.985 --> 38:00.570
- Ryan, you're up.
You ready?

38:00.570 --> 38:02.989
- Yes, sir.
- All right, let's do this.

38:02.989 --> 38:05.992
<i>[tense music]</i>

38:05.992 --> 38:08.953
<i>[rock music]</i>

38:08.953 --> 38:15.794
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:19.798 --> 38:21.633
- Well played.

38:21.633 --> 38:24.469
- Well, Ryan,
your blade held up really well.

38:24.469 --> 38:27.222
There's a little glinting.

38:27.222 --> 38:28.973
I like how the langet are wide.

38:28.973 --> 38:30.642
They stay
out of the way of my arm.

38:30.642 --> 38:34.354
They don't bang into me.
I love the styling, beautiful.

38:34.354 --> 38:37.273
In all, it held up really well.
- Thank you, sir.

38:37.273 --> 38:38.775
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:38.775 --> 38:40.276
- All right, gentleman.

38:40.276 --> 38:41.736
To test the sharpness
of your blade,

38:41.736 --> 38:43.822
I'll be attacking our
cane man here.

38:43.822 --> 38:45.782
So, Nicholas, you're up first.
Are you ready for this?

38:45.782 --> 38:47.492
- I'm ready.
Let's do it.

38:47.492 --> 38:50.453
<i>[tense music]</i>

38:50.453 --> 38:52.205
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:52.205 --> 38:55.166
<i>[rock music]</i>

38:55.166 --> 38:58.419
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:58.419 --> 39:01.756
- Nice.
- All right, Nicholas.

39:01.756 --> 39:05.385
Design-wise,
these sharp corners?

39:05.385 --> 39:07.262
Man, that's just
straight up dangerous.

39:07.262 --> 39:10.515
They're skin-tearing monsters.
But it's sharp.

39:10.515 --> 39:12.578
It's a good cutter.
- Thank you.

39:15.353 --> 39:16.563
- Ryan, you're up.
You ready?

39:16.563 --> 39:18.273
- Yes, sir.
- Okay.

39:18.273 --> 39:20.233
<i>- I had trouble</i>
<i>cutting the pig,</i>

39:20.233 --> 39:22.861
and now, we're back to sharp.

39:22.861 --> 39:25.363
<i>I don't know how</i>
<i>I'm going to do on this.</i>

39:25.363 --> 39:28.324
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

39:28.324 --> 39:33.162
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:36.708 --> 39:39.794
- Nice.
- All right.

39:39.794 --> 39:41.838
What we've got here,
your blade is definitely sharp.

39:41.838 --> 39:44.716
I can feel that sharp edge.
But it's a very obtuse edge.

39:44.716 --> 39:46.801
It kind of gets thick quickly.

39:46.801 --> 39:50.305
When you cut with this weapon,
you're cutting down, this way.

39:50.305 --> 39:52.140
So having that support
along your wrist

39:52.140 --> 39:54.058
is a good thing.

39:54.058 --> 39:55.393
I think you did
a beautiful job.

39:55.393 --> 39:57.270
It's definitely a cutter.

39:57.270 --> 39:59.480
Well done.
- Thank you, sir.

39:59.480 --> 40:01.482
<i>[tense music]</i>

40:01.482 --> 40:03.067
- Nicholas, Ryan.

40:03.067 --> 40:05.153
Only one of you
can move forward

40:05.153 --> 40:08.448
to the Tournament of Champions
to represent the armorer class.

40:08.448 --> 40:10.366
And that armorer is...

40:10.366 --> 40:12.869
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

40:12.869 --> 40:14.787
Nicholas.

40:14.787 --> 40:17.248
Congratulations, you are the
"Forged in Fire" champion

40:17.248 --> 40:19.125
for the armorer class.

40:19.125 --> 40:22.545
Ryan, unfortunately, your blade
did not make the cut.

40:22.545 --> 40:25.924
- In the kill test,
I tried multiple times

40:25.924 --> 40:28.384
<i>with your edge</i>
<i>to slice the pig open,</i>

40:28.384 --> 40:30.386
and it just wouldn't do that.

40:30.386 --> 40:32.680
It's for that reason
we're sending you home.

40:32.680 --> 40:35.600
- Ryan, please surrender
your hooded katar.

40:35.600 --> 40:37.018
<i>[hammer clangs]</i>

40:37.018 --> 40:38.728
<i>[fire sizzles]</i>

40:38.728 --> 40:40.772
- I'm always busy
kicking out armor.

40:40.772 --> 40:43.358
I will probably do
some more blades in the future

40:43.358 --> 40:44.901
because they liked what I did.

40:44.901 --> 40:46.903
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:46.903 --> 40:48.446
<i>I think Nicholas</i>
<i>is going to do great</i>

40:48.446 --> 40:49.697
<i>in the</i>
<i>Tournament of Champions.</i>

40:49.697 --> 40:51.449
<i>He's got a lot of skill,</i>

40:51.449 --> 40:53.618
and he's got a really good
head on his shoulders.

40:53.618 --> 40:56.329
<i>And that's what matters</i>
<i>at the end of the day.</i>

40:56.329 --> 40:58.790
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:58.790 --> 41:00.917
- Nicholas, congratulations,
You are the "Forged in Fire"

41:00.917 --> 41:03.044
<i>champion for the</i>
<i>armorer class.</i>

41:03.044 --> 41:05.213
<i>You'll be moving forward into</i>
<i>our Tournament of Champions</i>

41:05.213 --> 41:09.258
to fight for the title
and a check for $50,000.

41:09.258 --> 41:12.220
How you feeling right now?
- This is--this is amazing.

41:12.220 --> 41:14.931
Thank you guys very much.
I had a wonderful time.

41:14.931 --> 41:18.434
- Please present your katar
to your judges.

41:18.434 --> 41:20.770
<i>- I am the</i>
<i>"Forged in Fire" champion!</i>

41:20.770 --> 41:22.897
Boom.

41:22.897 --> 41:24.607
<i>Made it to</i>
<i>the Tournament of Champions.</i>

41:24.607 --> 41:26.192
<i>I get to represent</i>
<i>the armorers,</i>

41:26.192 --> 41:28.069
<i>and I get to show</i>
<i>the metalworkers,</i>

41:28.069 --> 41:30.697
<i>farriers, and blacksmiths</i>
<i>how to make a knife.</i>

41:30.697 --> 41:32.657
I really can't wait.
I'm really interested to see

41:32.657 --> 41:35.201
what the Tournament of
Champions is going to bring me.

41:35.201 --> 41:38.121
<i>[rock music]</i>

41:38.121 --> 41:41.958
<i>♪ ♪</i>
